│ This is an interesting bug. The root cause analysis is spot  │
│ on: the VPlan cost model miscalculates the cost of a `shl`   │
│ instruction with a loop-invariant shift amount, causing a    │
│ discrepancy with the legacy cost model and triggering an     │
│ assertion. The key is to make the VPlan cost model aware of  │
│ uniform shifts.                                              │
│                                                              │
│ The costing for `VPWidenRecipe` (which handles `shl`) is     │
│ done in `VPWidenRecipe::computeCost` in                      │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp`. I will     │
│ modify this function to correctly identify and cost uniform  │
│ shifts.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ My plan is to:                                               │
│ 1.  Separate the `case` statements for shift instructions    │
│ (`shl`, `lshr`, `ashr`) from other binary operations within  │
│ `VPWidenRecipe::computeCost`.                                │
│ 2.  For shift instructions, add logic to determine if the    │
│ shift amount is uniform. A shift amount is uniform if it's a │
│ loop-invariant value. This can be checked by seeing if the   │
│ `VPValue` for the shift amount is defined outside the loop   │
│ region or is a known constant-like value.                    │
│ 3.  Pass this uniformity information to                      │
│ `TTI.getArithmeticInstrCost`. This function has an overload  │
│ that accepts a `VectorCostKind` parameter (`VCS_Uniform` or  │
│ `VCS_Variable`), which allows the target-specific cost model │
│ to provide a more accurate cost.                             │
│                                                              │
│ This change will align the VPlan cost model with the legacy  │
│ one for this case, resolving the assertion.                  │
│                                                              │
